@case: I found 2 recipes that contain yellow rice on the NYT site:
--Yellow Rice
--Lentils With Chorizo, Greens and Yellow Rice

@DS
I try to be accommodating but when it comes to garlic 
I am not nearly as forgiving as you ~ if someone doesn't like garlic they have every right to abstain from eating the offending dish and simply choose to enjoy something else being offered. Garlic is simply one of life's pleasures on which  I cannot compromise.

@Rothkosmom
You do have the right to cut, slice, grate, grind, chop, flatten, etc., your cabbage any way you choose. 
No cabbage brigade will come and haul you off to the food reformatory for doing something original to your cabbage as it is  and always will be . . . Your cabbage!!

@memie Hardie Try eating it with more rice and think of it as a side dish to go alongside the rice. So you’re using it as a seasoning for the rice. 

Reading Fuchsia’s books are really enlightening on how to actually eat Chinese dishes properly. They aren’t meant to be eaten like a western dish. 

Fuchsia is one of the greatest scholars on Chinese Cuisine living today. Her work is humbling to experience.
